{"type":"message","id":"29cd13ea","parentId":"c52909c8","timestamp":"2026-04-14T16:33:35.541Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I see. The `__init__` has `sign=None` as a parameter, which shadows the imported `sign` function. When `XhsClient()` is called without arguments, `sign` is `None`, and `self.external_sign = sign` sets it to `None`.\n\nThe fix: change `self.external_sign = sign` to use the module-level `sign` when the parameter is None. I need to reference the module-level `sign` differently. Since I'm reading from the installed file, I'll need to patch it.\n\nOne way: `self.external_sign = sign if sign is not None else __import__('xhs.help').help.sign`\n\n\nBut that's ugly. Actually, in the context of the `__init__` method, `sign` refers to the parameter (which is None), NOT the module-level import. The parameter shadows the module-level name. The fix should be to use the module-level import explicitly.\n\nLet me think about how to patch this properly. The module-level `sign` is imported via `from xhs.help import sign`. In the `__init__` method, `sign` refers to the parameter. I need to change the assignment to reference the module-level function instead—something like checking if the parameter is None and falling back to the imported `sign`.\n\nI could also just rename the parameter to `custom_sign` to avoid the shadowing issue altogether. Let me check what the actual line is in the file and apply the fix.","thinkingSignature":"d82d5d515eca8380d02f7181961ebea8334e4c109efb754a7fb22098a33b25a5"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_c854kan0qqhs_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"python3 << 'EOF'\ncontent = open('/home/ai/.local/lib/python3.8/site-packages/xhs/core.py').read()\n\n# Fix: when sign parameter is None, use the imported sign from help module\nold = \"        self.external_sign = sign\\n\"\nnew = \"        from xhs.help import sign as _sign; self.external_sign = sign if sign is not None else _sign\\n\"